<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-03-05T09:40:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-03-05T09:40:00-05:00" n="263" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d263">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 839.51/1258.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Santo Domingo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-03-05T10:00:00-04:40">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 5, 1914, 10 a.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>In considering solution of financial problem can you loan money against
                            alcohol and tobacco taxes on condition that said taxes shall be
                            collected by Receivership? With the right to collect this tax General
                            Receiver’s hands would be strengthened to the extent that he could aid
                            materially in maintaining law and order by practically policing the
                            country. Vick and I agree that this advantage would be most important in
                            the work of establishing orderly government.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Sullivan</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>